CLINICAL HISTORY:  Epilepsy, currently seizure-free.
MEDICATIONS:   Lamictal, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A 38-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy, current seizure­
free.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Digital video EEG is performed using standard
10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation. This is an awake through stage II sleep record in an individual who is very drowsy.
In maximum wakefulness there is an 8.8 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm. Vertex waves are noted in sleep, as are post.
Hyperventilation produces a small degree of background slowing. The patient is falling asleep in photic stimulation.
Heart rate 60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits but excessively drowsy patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are noted. The excessive drowsiness can be due to sleep deprivations, medications or a warm environment.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old male with recurrent vertigo and fatigue.
MEDICATIONS: Os-Cal, Nexium, Lexapro, Albuterol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with 9.5 Hz 40 mcv posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized
by slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles are observed
in stage 2 sleep. Photic stimulation is performed after the patient has been asleep.
There is a driving response observed, though the patient is drifting in an out of sleep.
Hyperventilation produces a scant amount of background slowing.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed in this EEG. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important
consideration, a repeat study capturing one of his spells is advised.

CLINICAL HISTORY:    38 year old right handed woman with migraine headaches, depression and a sharp pain in her head.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax, Seroquel, Zolpidem, Nabumetone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness background EEG is well-organized. There is a relatively fast alpha rhythm of 12 Hz with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Hyperventilation produces an increased in amplitude of the background. This is followed by a drowsy and then stage I sleep with vertex waves and posts. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation are performed concurrently and do not active the record. In fact, the patient seems to drift into stage II sleep at the close of this study.
HR: 	66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  	28 year old right handed woman with a possible TIA or stroke
July 2009 with left-sided numbness, weakness,  memory loss.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, Amitriptyline, Motrin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic simulation is performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately  organized with 10.5 Hz, 30 microvolt alpha rhythm and a small amount of wicket activity. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in the record. A  normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of seizure or stroke and correlation with imaging and history may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	22 year old right handed woman with severe asthma and episodes of right sided shaking, trembling, loss of consciousness, and incontinence. These have occurred in clusters for the past 2 years.

Photic stimulation elicits driving. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Drowsiness increases the synchronicity of the record.
HR: 	60-70 bpm

CLINICAL HISTORY:   44 year old woman with HIV, epilepsy, bipolar disease. Seizures in April and July 2009 after patient stopped her Trileptal.

MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol, Reyataz, Combivir, Seroquel, ASA, Prazosin, Dapsone, Levemir

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is low voltage, but there is
an 8.5 hertz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of background beta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in slowing in the background. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta followed by an increase in theta. Hypersynchronous activity is noted in drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

HR: 	90 bpm

IMPRESSION:   EEG at the limits of normal.

CLINICAL CORR  ELATION: There are no epileptiform features observed. If further characterization of her epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing sleep is advised.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	39 year old right handed male with daily headaches, evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Cyclobenzaprine,  Zolpidem, Elavil, Cymbalta, Norvasc, Gabapentin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and primarily asleep EEG with photic stimulation but without hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The majority of the record includes stage I and stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and posts.   The patient is awakened for photic stimulation and has limited wakefulness.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  The primarily sleep EEG could be due to sleep deprivation or other disturbances like hypersomnolence, or even a sleep-deprived EEG. There are no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   48 year old male with a history of tremor during sleep which began in July 2009.  The patient has a history of an MVA in June 2009 and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:  Valtrex, Nexium, Singulair, Metoprolol, Verapamil, Furosemide, Doxazosin, Flax seed oil, Omega fish oil.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low-voltage but well­ defined 10 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Features of drowsiness include an increase of beta.  Hyperventilation produces background slowing.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy, and a low-voltage pattern is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old right handed male with a feeling of disequilibrium
and presyncope, admitted in July 2009.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10
Hz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an
increase in background slowing. Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes,
spindles and POSTS. The patient is quite sleepy and transitions in and out of stage II
sleep. The POSTS are of slightly higher amplitude on the left. Hyperventilation
produces an increase in amplitude. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The
amplitude asymmetry of the POSTS is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old female presented with syncope and toe ulceration.
MEDICATIONS: Vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation was
preformed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the
record. There is an 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified. Features of drowsiness
including increase in beta followed by vertexes, K complexes, and spindles. With
arousal, the patient does achieve an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation elicits
scant driving.
HR: 104 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	28 year old woman with multiple events in the clinic today admitted with episode of unresponsiveness  and mutism.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.  The patient is awake and cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a well defined 9.3 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage fronto-central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by the appearance of rhythmic theta.
HR: 	90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed in this record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Of note, this record was
recorded immediately after this patient's multiple and prolonged events. Hence, not only were the behaviors unusual for seizures, but there was no postictal slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   59 year old right handed female with headaches and sharp occipital pain.

MEDICATIONS: None

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is awake for most of the study, however, is in and out of drowsiness.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG shows a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with 25 mV.  In addition, when drowsy the patient has 5 Hz temporal waves and some vertex waves.  Also noted is a rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness (RMTD) which is a normal variant, entered during photic stimulation.  The patient is seen to have driving at 7 Hz.



HR  :


84 bpm with occasional PVCs when drowsy.



IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy  Clinical evaluation of PVCs in sleep may be valuable.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	28 year old right handed male with a history of epilepsy with the onset at the age of 5.  The patient has been seizure-free for approximately 5 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard  10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The study is performed with photic stimulation and hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient begins the study in wakefulness and displays a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with 50 mV. There is higher amplitude on the left than

HR:	N/A
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform activity is noted. A normal EEG do not exclude diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  34 year old right handed woman with epilepsy since age 14

2009.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are seen.  In this individual with epilepsy, a more prolonged study capturing more extensive sleep may be helpful to identify epileptiform activity, and the beta may be due to anxiety.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awaken and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively
low voltage. There is excess theta in the background and a hint of 9 Hz alpha rhythm.
Later portions of the record demonstrate a more vigorous 10 Hz posterior dominant
rhythm. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, but the patient is drifting into stage
2 sleep.
HR: 56 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed in this record
today. There were only on 1 occasion some focal theta in the right central temporal
region. The only other abnormality is really an excess of theta or a variable degree of
background slowing or disorganization. On the whole, these findings are less prominent
than in previous studies. Many years ago there was a vertex spike while awake, but that
was not seen today.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 44 year old female with epilepsy since age 19, with nocturnal tonic-clonic seizures with incontinence, hypertension, hyperlipidemia. Seizures were related to an assault at age 19.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Gabapentin, Remeron
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.3 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in background theta. There are occasional bursts of paroxysmal rhythmic slowing noted as the patient transitions from hyperventilation into stage I sleep. Brief epochs of paroxysmal slowing are noted as she transitions into sleep with vertex waves. The pattern is overall most reminiscent of hypnagogic hypersynchrony but there is a suggestion of asynchrony in the bursts. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The overall organization is acceptable. There is hypnagogic hypersynchrony which is at the limits of organization. In this individual with a history of epilepsy, additional EEG recordings may be valuable to delineate underlying epileptiform activity as well as to determine if there is an epileptiform discharge hidden in the hypnagogic hypersynchrony. Hypnagogic hypersynchrony, however, is a normal finding.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake record.

After photic stimulation is over, the patient had some jerking of her shoulders but not in association with the flashing lights. After the photic stimulation continues, the recording continues and the patient had intermittent jerking of her shoulders. The shoulders jerk forwards and backwards.

The shoulder jerking is not associated with epileptiform activity in the EEG. It is sometimes associated with upwards thrusting of her upper chest. She stares straight ahead during the events.

As the record continues, a physician examines the patient. The interaction with the physician and the patient is associated with increasing motor activity including eye blinking, mouth opening and closing, a little bit of alternating movements to right or left, and then some rotatory movements of the torso. When the movements stop, the EEG shows a normal awake pattern. The patient is staring off to space after the event ends.

The event begins at 9:58 and lasts 7 minutes. Afterwards, there is intermittent jerking. Cognitive testing is not performed to make certain that the patient is responsive at the end of the EEG.

HR: 60 bpm


IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient had a 7-minute behavioral episode without EEG change. This recording suggests a behavioral event rather than an electrical seizure.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. Abundant stage II sleep includes vertex, K complexes, spindles and POSTS. On one occasion in hyperventilation, there is a single burst of shifting slowing. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing scant slowing and an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage II sleep and does not clearly activate the record.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. This EEG may be compared to 2004 EEG as well as other prior studies.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 31 year old right-handed woman with seizures for the last 5

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed male with epilepsy, hepatitis C and liver
disease admitted after multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were
performed. The patient had one of his spells during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm with
occasional background theta particularly in the temporal regions. Hyperventilation is performed
early-on in the record producing an increase in generalized slowing. This is follow by
drowsiness with increased rhythmic slowing followed by vertex waves, K complexes, spindles
and then arousals.
At 11:59, the patient is awake. He shifts about. He is awake during photic stimulation which
elicits a brief driving response.
The patient has a spell during the EEG. This is at 12:10. at 12:10:56, he is moving about. He is
unresponsive with a technician. During the section at 12:10:52, the patient has right facial
twitching and he has some movements of his left arm. He does not answer questions to the
technologist. The patient is not entirely on camera. The EEG demonstrates an awake pattern
with an artifact at C3T3. He is amnestic for the event. Unfortunately during this spell the
technician is trying to repair the C3 electrode. He is described as having alternating right facial
or left hand movements. There is no definitive EEG signature for these behaviors.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits but with unusual behavior.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the electrode problems, there was no EEG scalp
signature for this patient's behavior.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 25 year old right handed woman with episodes which are described as spasms. They include eye fluttering, head rocking and crying. Her brother and her child both have epilepsy.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a symmetric, 11 Hz, 70 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces a great deal of blinking. Brief drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of theta and some bursts of rhythmic, hypnagogic hypersynchrony. Photic stimulation elicits abundant, symmetric driving. The patient has an event during photic stimulation characterized by frequent eye blink. The eye blink frequency increases after the photic stimulation stops. She has shaking of her legs and impaired responsiveness. This is followed by moaning. No epileptiform features are associated with these behaviors. The EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern throughout these behaviors which began at 11:44. unfortunately, the camera is primarily on her face and upper body and this is the lower extremity activity. Afterward, the patient has intermittent arm shaking noted at 11:47, again difficult to see on the camera. Afterward she feels drained and tired but the EEG continues to demonstrate a normal awake pattern.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second EEG for this individual. During both EEGs, the patient had behaviors characteristic of nonepileptic seizures with characteristic behavior, crying in the absence of epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed gentleman with a long history of depression, epilepsy, cerebral palsy, subsequent aneurysm repair. Last seizure 05/11/2011 with loss of consciousness and confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Dilantin, Norvasc, Simvastatin, Sertraline, Amlodipine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall EEG is relatively low voltage with generous beta and scant alpha rhythms. A breech rhythm is noted in the right hemisphere. There is also some electrode artifact, compatible with a deformity of the skull shape.
Hyperventilation is performed early in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude, augmenting the double phase reversing artifacts on the right and increasing some theta a bit more so on the right compared to the left. Features of drowsiness included increase in beta. In drowsiness, the focal slowing is a bit more apparent on the right with a mixture of rhythmic 3-5 Hz activity. Vertex waves are noted as the patient transitions in and out of sleep. There is  disruption of faster frequency activity on the right in the transition to sleep in the centrotemporal regions with a bit more prominent spindles in the central regions, in the region of the previous
craniotomy. Overall, most of the focal slowing in this record is centrotemporal. In the context of a breech rhythm, there are a handful of right central or frontal sharp waves. Photic stimulation is  performed while the patient is in stage 2 sleep. No significant driving response was noted.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: A normal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic theta and delta activity in the right temporal region.
2. Rare G4 and F4 sharp waves identified in the context of a breech rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to previous studies, the EEG today has primarily centrotemporal slowing. The sharp waves are ipsilateral to the previous craniotomy and similar to the previous records. There is some variability in terms of localization of epileptiform activity
in the right for this individual.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   32 year old right handed woman with new onset of seizures who was unconsciousness, unable to speak, and left face twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lovenox
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, patient events, and alarms, as well as nurses events were noted to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  In the middle of the night some electrodes became dislodged and there is some electrode artifact by the end of the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm at 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  Activating procedures and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep and normal stages I to III with sleep are recorded.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Episodes:  The patient had 3 episodes throughout the recording.  The first one occurred at 12:34 p.m. at the onset of the recording where she started having left facial twitching, followed by unresponsiveness while continuing to have left facial twitching.  This event lasted for about 2 minutes and then the patient became reactive again.
The second event occurred at 8:18 p.m.  The patient suddenly started having left facial twitching and grimacing, as well as tightening her arms, as well as becoming unresponsive.  This was followed by staring and mouth movements.  The episode lasted for over 4 minutes.
At about 3:32 a.m. the patient suddenly started having diffuse body shaking and rocking, as well as facial twitching.  This was much more severe than the other ones.  She continued rocking, jerking, and being unresponsive.  Then after stopping the jerking she laid in bed and remained unresponsive and started moving her mouth rhythmically in a chewing fashion.  The whole event lasted for about 4.5 minutes.
The EEG during the whole 3 events revealed a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform correlate to any of the events.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG and 3 non-epileptic events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  Note:  The 3 events described above did not have an EEG correlate which is consistent with a diagnosis of psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  39 year old right handed male with history of right ankle pain and narcotic abuse, now with episodes of loss of consciousness with diffuse body shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside for 4.5 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were performed.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, as well as patient alarm events, and nurses notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm with normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Events:  The patient had about 9 events which consisted of him pressing the alarm, suddenly his arms would become flexed, and he would become stiff and grimacing his face, lasting for about 20-30 seconds, during the episode and after which he would be unresponsive for another 2-3 minutes.  The behavior was very similar to the ones that he described before and every episode remained the same.  During these episodes the EEG would have a diffuse muscle artifact, but underlying it there would be a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform discharges prior to the flexing, posturing, or after when he would remain unresponsive.  It looked like a normal EEG.  Sometimes with the flexor posturing he would hip thrust during the event.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with events with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The events that were captured and described as above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.  No epileptiform discharges were seen.

HR:    50 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Hypnagogic hypersynchrony is a normal finding.  The single burst of rhythmic slowing from the left is a nonspecific finding.  To more
completely characterize this patient's epilepsy, a more prolonged study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient recalls 3 episodes.  The first is on the 19th at noon where she felt a little startled.  The second was at 10 p.m. where she felt a mini aura characterized by tingling sensation on her face.  She did not recall an episode at 5:25, although she did push the button for a tingling sensation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Random wakefulness and sleep includes a well-organized 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage frontocentral beta activity.
Event time 11:22:  There is a burst of rhythmic left temporal theta delta with frequency evolution.  This is 5 seconds in duration.  There is no push button at that time.
Event time 5:25:20 p.m.:   A burst of rhythmic theta, frequency was subtle, frequency evolution lasting only 3 seconds.  Thirty seconds later the patient reports the mini-aura which she no longer recalled.
Event time 9:58 p.m.  No abnormalities on the EEG were identified at that time.
Event time10:25 a.m.:  There was another burst lasting 4 seconds in duration in the morning on the 20th which is similar to the 2 prior bursts.   No clinical features were recalled.
HR:    60 bpm
INTERVAL IMPRESSION:  There are 3 bursts of rhythmic theta from the left temporal region with frequency evolution.  These are concerning as a potential interictal epileptiform discharge.  They may also be clinically significant with the mini-auras that the patient experienced.

Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta.  The drowsy pattern is relatively symmetric and on rare occasions, the slow activity seems to be slightly slower on the right compared to the left.  This is more apparent with the use of frequency analysis.  Hyperventilation produces bilateral theta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous, bilateral driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving. On some occasions, the supraharmonic driving seems to be bit a more prominent on the right.

IMPRESSION:   EEG is at the limit of normal.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG was performed for 24 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. EVENT:  During the recording the patient had 5 events where he would suddenly start shaking his head from side to side.  Sometimes towards the left and sometimes toward the right irregularly while becoming unresponsive and remaining so for minutes at time, sometimes for more than 5-10 minutes, and intermittently starting and stopping the behavior. CLINICAL HISTORY:  18 year old right handed female syncopal spell lasting 25 seconds.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and a sleep record in very drowsy individual.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, exceeding 70 mV with posterior slow waves of youth.  In drowsiness there is hypersynchronous rhythmic higher amplitude theta frequency activity “hypnogogic”, “hypersynchrony”.  There were 1 or 2 points of head rocking artifact and there were 1-2 bursts which are slightly asynchronous. Hyperventilation produces hypersynchronous rhythmic high amplitude, somewhat sharply contoured theta frequency activity, but no definitive spike and wave activity. The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Other features of drowsiness include the hypersynchronous rhythmic theta.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG demonstrates multiple normal variants for a young adult.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There was no definitive spike and wave activity, although hyperventilation did produce some rhythmic high amplitude theta.  There were a handful of slightly asynchronous bursts as the patient transitions to drowsiness.  If absence seizures are an important consideration, a repeat fasting EEG, perhaps with a second hyperventilation session maybe helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  42 year old right handed woman with life long migraine headaches, now with an early morning headache with lightheadedness and dry mouth, but without visual phenomenon. MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Elavil
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Mu activity, as well as lambda was identified. The patient appears to be very sleepy, transitions in and out of stage II sleep.  Spindle activity is noted.  There seem to be fragments of sleep spindles just as she is dropping almost in and out wakefulness.  As the sleep record continues, more abundant stage II sleep is identified, but in the transition in and out of stage II sleep, there are fragments of early drowsiness, almost emerging into a stage II sleep pattern. The patient is awakened at the end of the test and answers complex questions. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:   66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Somewhat unusual, but normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features, but there are multiple normal variants, including mu and rhythmic temporal theta of drowsiness. Given the transitions noted early in the record between wakefulness and stage II sleep, an underlying sleep deficit may account for this.  If there is any other question, a follow up study when the patient has had adequate sleep may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  32 year old man with a history of TBI in 1998, admitted after having an episode of tonic-clonic seizure, brought to the emergency department where he had another seizure and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Pantoprazole, Depakote
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient's impedances were inappropriate, specifically in the occipital electrodes which caused some multi-electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that appears to reach 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient had some normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures did not produce any abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I/stage II.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
One single sharp transient maximal at F3 seen in the recording while drowsy.
Occasional small amplitude sharp spikes seen at T3, only in stage I sleep, although not seen over T2.  The morphology is most consistent with benign epileptiform transients of sleep (BETS).
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal limited EEG with one suspicious left frontal sharp transient and BETS.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The significance of the left frontal sharp transient is unclear.  A repeated recording should be performed.  Particularly in this patient where the impedances and the quality of the recording was poor, it should be repeated free of charge.  The BETS are benign and do not indicate a high correlation with an epileptogenic focus in that region.

INTRODUCTION:  The recording was done according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 11-12 Hz alpha that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  During drowsiness there is an increased amount of theta and delta as well as attenuation of the posterior dominant rhythm.  Stage II sleep is not recorded.  Hyperventilation is performed with a fair effort and does not produce significant background change.  Step photic stimulation produces mild driving at  higher frequencies.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 25 minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy persists a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.

Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal wake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 68-year-old woman who was talking to a friend, had a brief loss of consciousness while sitting at the table.  The patient reports not being post ictal, does not describe any symptoms to suggest a seizure.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.7 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Other features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
Heart rate:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted in the EEG.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG capturing patient during wakefulness.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Syncope versus seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 34-year-old right-handed woman who presents with history of motor vehicle accident with loss of consciousness while driving.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard international 10/20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed with tracing captures wakefulness only.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 10 Hz in frequency and 30-40 microvolt in amplitude seen in the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies with no driving response.  Heart rate was 70-80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capture in wakefulness only. No epileptiform abnormalities or seizure were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG, does not rule the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deep stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG maybe helpful.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  52 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 66-year-old woman who presents with 6-7 months of intermittent left eye and mouth twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  Coreg, Metformin, aspirin, and simvastatin.
INTRODUCTION:  The study was done according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low amplitude, well-formed and modulated 10-11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eye opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency with a gradient.  During drowsiness, roving eye movements, POSTS (posterior occipital sharp transients of sleep), and bursts of diffuse theta and delta are captured.  Stage II sleep is not recorded.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces mild diffuse symmetric background slowing.  Step photic stimulation induces symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  Occasional premature atrial contractions are captured on a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Occasional premature atrial contractions captured on the single EKG lead.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal 52 minute awake and drowsy EEG.  No epileptiform discharges are captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.  Premature atrial contractions are captured on the single EKG lead.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old woman with epilepsy, recent prolonged seizure with loss of awareness.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Keppra, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  Posterior slow waves of youth were observed.  Drowsiness is characterized by hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.
Hyperventilation was performed with good effort producing an increasing an increase in amplitude of the background.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
A single left temporal sharp wave was noted in early drowsiness.
Heart rate:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A single left temporal sharp wave cannot be considered pathological and must be considered artifact.
This is the third EEG for this patient in 4 years.  At age 18 she had 3 Hz spike and wave activity, but this has not been seen in the more recent studies.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 83-year-old woman with COPD status post aneurysm repair x2 with 2 days of shortness of breath, evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, Norvasc, vancomycin, prednisone, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a diffusely slow pattern.  Sections of the record include stage II sleep with spindles and posts.  Stimulation of the patient produces a brief arousal with a 9-Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  This is followed by a somewhat slower pattern.
Heart rate 114 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were identified in this EEG.  When the patient is first stimulated, there is a normal awake pattern and then some background slowing, compatible with a drowsy patient.  Clinical correlation regarding the patient's hypersomnolence may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 51-year-old woman admitted for a syncopal episode lasting 10-15 minutes followed by lethargy and confusion.

Hyperventilation produces a small amount of slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were identified.  This seems to be a very drowsy patient.

Stage II sleep.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 36-year-old woman with migraines and seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Topamax, flecainide, cetirizine, many others.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 28-year-old man who presents with an episode of loss of consciousness with associated fall, shaking and postictal confusion.  The patient states that it might have been his third episode of such nature.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  None.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The record was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 12 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  Frequent slow and fast alpha variants are present.  There is anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Throughout the recording there are frequent polymorphic intrusions of diffuse theta and delta.  Drowsiness is present, but stage II sleep is not recorded.  Hyperventilation results in mild diffuse symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy 23 minute EEG.  Diffuse intrusions of theta and delta activity likely represent a normal variant.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old male with epilepsy since age 12.  Subsequent cocaine dependence.  After a seizure, patient became violent.  Seizures characterized by an aura of strange feeling followed by postictal confusion.  Last seizure 1 day ago. The patient asked the technologist if photic stimulation would produce 1 of his typical seizures.  The technologist told him that, that was a possibility.  The patient subsequently had 1 of typical behaviors during photic stimulation, but after the photic stimulation had stopped.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a scant amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the EEG and produces and increase an amplitude of the background.  Vertex waves and POSTS are observed in stage 1 sleep with brief stage 2 sleep.  The patient was falling asleep during photic stimulation and transitioning in and out of sleep during photic stimulation.
The patient had an event during photic stimulation.  The patient was drowsy prior to photic stimulations, the patient was waking up, although there were brief transitions in and out of sleep.
The patient was awake at the end of the 11 Hz stimuli, when the behavior occurred, he sat up abruptly.  His eyes were dilated, he was moving back and forth and his heart rate increased briefly to 150 BPM.
Although the audio was not working, the patient was able to communicate during the event.
There were no epileptiform features noted during the event.  No postictal features were identified.
Heart rate 78-150 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  The EEG is normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient had an unusual behavior.  The patient was clearly awake for several seconds prior to the event, but he had been drifting in and out of sleep.  The event had no epileptiform features, but a link either to a sleep-related disorder or a psychiatric illness may be considered.

As the patient becomes drowsy, theta is identified from the temporal regions bilaterally.
Mu activity was noted, but testing was not performed to confirm this.
Photic stimulation was performed as the patient was drifting off to sleep, but did elicit a driving response.  Photic stimulation elicited harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third EEG for this individual.  The first EEG immediately after his symptoms was associated with left temporal focal slowing, but this EEG is normal.

INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.   Hyperventilation was noted performed.  Photic stimulation was  performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated 10.5 to 11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.
During sleep symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles, and K-complexes are captured.  Intermittent independent and synchronous polymorphic theta and delta activity is captured over the bilateral temporal regions.

Occasional bilateral temporal slowing.
Phase II Sleep
No epileptiform discharges.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy since 18 months of age. The patient reports grand mal, petite mal and complex partial seizures.  The seizures occur during sleep, the last seizure was 10 days ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Gabapentin, Provera, Excedrin, ibuprofen, Dulera, may others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz 40 microvolt alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Prominent mu activity is noted with 8 Hz activity in the central regions particularly on the left although testing was not performed to confirm this.  Mu rhythm was also noted in the right central region as the recording continued.  Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  The overall EEG is relatively high voltage with a very prominent mu activity.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Drowsiness produces an increase in beta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.  In some sections of the record there is a question of an alpha sub-harmonic.
Heart rate 72 b.p.m.
IMPRESSION:  This is an interesting but normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient has an interesting but normal EEG including the mu activity and the alpha rhythm with the alpha supra-harmonic.  No epileptiform features were identified.  If additional information is needed to characterize this individual's epilepsy, a more prolonged study can be considered.  Although benzodiazepines were not listed in this patient's medications, benzodiazepines or other similar medications might account for the prominent beta noted in the record.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 26-year-old right-handed man with a history of head trauma from car accident.  The patient stated that he started having seizure-like activity after car accident.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Xanax.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to T1 and T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was performed.  Photic stimulation was not performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through stage II of sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 12 Hz in frequency, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  Stage 2 sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes, sleep spindles, and posts.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background.  Heart rate is 70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through a stage 2 sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy, if seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old male with a history of seizures and hypertension presents with seizure-like activities described as acting weird, staring, confusion, and EMS noted generalized tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include phenobarbital and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using the standard international 10/20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1-channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through a stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8.5-9 Hz in frequency and 30-35 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 6-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness.  There is presence of low amplitude diffuse beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm and slowing of the background activity and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of the vertex sharp waves.  Stage II sleep was captured characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles. Heart rate was 90-100 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to toxic metabolic hypoxic or infectious encephalopathy, alternatively it could be due to the effect of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including phenobarbital or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform discharges abnormalities or seizures were captured during this record.  If clinically indicated, a repeat sleep deprived EEG or continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.  The absence of epileptiform activities or seizures does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old man with a past medical history of adult onset seizures who presented with 2 episodes of generalized tonic-clonic seizures.  The patient remained lethargic.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Ativan, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG monitoring was performed using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Records were daily reviewed for EEG abnormalities and clinical events, wakefulness, stage 2 sleep, and a slow wave sleep were captured.  There was an automated spike and seizure detection system in place as well as the patient activated alarm system.  The patient was drowsy with short periods of wakefulness during this recording.
Interictal EEG:  In the most alert state, there was a posterior dominant rhythm with a frequency of 9-9.5 Hz and 25-40 microvolts seen in the occipital region, which attenuated with eye opening.  There was presence of low-amplitude diffuse beta frequency, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness, stage 1 and a stage 2 sleep were seen during the most part of this recording.  Stage 1 sleep was characterized by the disappearance of the alpha rhythm slowing of the background and absence of eye blink and muscle artifact, vertex sharp waves, and POSTS.  Stage 2 sleep was characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles, and POSTS.  The deeper stages of sleep have characterized by increasing amounts of delta frequency activity.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures were captured during this recording.  Heart rate was 90 to 110 beats per minute.
CLINICAL EVENTS:  No clinical events were captured during this recording.  The patient was drowsy, but arousable by calling the patient.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG monitoring study capturing short periods of wakefulness and for the most part of the recording drowsiness stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures noted during this recording.  This EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are of a clinical concern, a repeat prolonged video EEG monitoring may be helpful.  Please note that the patient was tachycardiac.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 47-year-old man with episodes of dizziness followed by loss of consciousness and decreased responsiveness.  His last episode was several days ago.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude of 11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening. No epileptiform discharges.
No stage 2 sleep.
Nearly continuous T3 electrode artifact.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake only, 22 minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persistent, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old woman admitted with an episode of transient dizziness.  Past history of hypertension, asthma and a psychiatric illness.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, lisinopril, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was attempted in the laboratory using standard a 10-20 System of electrode placement, with 1 channel of EKG.  Significant technical difficulties included the hair weaves that the patient has.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Despite the problems with electrode placement and impedance, the background EEG is appropriately organized, with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.  The referential montage was not particularly successful.  Features of drowsiness included an increase in background slowing.  In addition, very brief stage I sleep was seen, with vertex waves and then a transition in and out of stage I sleep.  At the very close of the record, the patient was transitioning in and out of stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.  Heart rate 84 bpm, occasional PVCs.
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging but normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The transitions in and out of stage II sleep may reflect sleep deprivation or an underlying sleep disturbance, which could be correlated with this patient's clinical picture.  To obtain a better quality EEG, a repeat study, when the patient has had her hair weaves removed, is suggested.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 60-year-old woman who presents with a history of dizzy spells, the most recent about 10 days ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Meclizine p.r.n., Pravachol, and amlodipine.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated low to moderate amplitude 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness, POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep) and vertex waves are captured.  Hyperventilation produces several bursts of diffuse polymorphic delta activity as well as mild symmetrical background slowing.  Photic stimulation results in occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  A single EKG lead reveals a regular heart rate.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 22-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured; however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persists, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 51-year-old man with the onset of seizures at the age of about 12 to 13 years of age.  In the last 20 years seizure semiology has changed.  Seizures are now characterized by an aura of strange sensations followed by loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.  During the events the patient has been told that he wanders.  He has multiple events per day, most of them are nocturnal.  Last such seizure was on 01/07/2013.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin extended release 200 mg twice a day and Tegretol extended release 200 mg b.i.d.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), vertex waves and sleep complexes are captured.  Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort and produces no significant change in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:  No epileptiform discharges to stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 27-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 19-year-old male with epilepsy, seizure free for the last 4 years.  Previous EEGs.  He has hearing impairment and attention deficit disorder.  At age 15 he had 2.5 Hz spike and wave activity on an outside EEG, but by age 17 his EEG had become normal.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 25-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy.  First ever seizure 04/27 with loss of consciousness, twisting and post ictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Klonopin, previously treated with tramadol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
TECHNICAL:  The patient appears to be somewhat tense.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  During much of the EEG, there is a little bit more relaxed wakefulness with slowing of the alpha rhythm to 8.5 Hz.  Drowsiness was characterized by an increase in beta.  Other features of drowsiness include rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness with vertex waves noted in stage I sleep.
During hyperventilation and in relaxed wakefulness, there are 2 simple sharp waves.  During hyperventilation the simple sharp waves are more clearly defined after going slow wave.
Photic stimulation was remarkable for prominent beta and prominent, supraharmonic driving.
Additionally, hyperventilation was remarkable for a fair amount of muscle artifact.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrated multiple, normal variants, some of which have the morphology of benign epileptiform discharges.  There is a single left mid to posterior temporal sharp wave.  In that there is only one discharge, this must be considered artifactual.  The generous beta described above may be due to this patient's medications.
If an underlying seizure disorder is an important consideration, a followup study with more prolonged sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21-year-old woman with epilepsy since the age of 8.  Most recent seizure June/July 2012 with fainting, falling, and shaking.  Now 4 months pregnant.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and asleep record.
TECHNICAL:  Impedances for most of the electrodes were satisfactory, but this EEG was problematic with a great degree of muscle artifact when the patient was awake.  As the patient went off to sleep, there was still muscle artifact picked up in the left scalp electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Despite the problems described above, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of focal frontal central beta.  Wicket was noted as the patient became drowsy.  Other features with drowsiness include rhythmic central theta.  The electrode artifact did not drop out in stage I sleep with vertex waves.  Brief stage II sleep included vertex waves with spindles.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation was remarkable for a great deal of muscle artifact.  Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging but otherwise normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The wicket is a normal finding.  Given the degree of muscle artifact described above, a follow-up study capturing perhaps more prolonged
sleep or with other mechanisms to alleviate the muscle artifact is suggested.  Alternatively, comparison with this individual's childhood EEGs may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 25-year-old female with history of new onset seizures described as having strange feeling, seeing colors and patterns, and bad smell followed by 30 seconds of loss of consciousness and post event confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal, Celexa.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, posterior dominant rhythm is 10 to 10.5 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which was distributed symmetrically.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 70 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness only.  No epileptiform abnormalities or electrographic seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are a clinical concern, prolonged EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 52-year-old woman with childhood epilepsy, break through seizures in 2004 & 2009, with recurrent a seizure in recent weeks requiring medication adjustment. Seizures in 2004 described as left-sided shaking with incontinence of bladder, lasting up to 30 minutes, 1-2 times per year.
MEDICATIONS:  Unclear.  No longer Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically satisfactory record with some head rocking.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there was a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements with attenuation of the alpha rhythm, alpha squeak was noted on occasion.  Other features of the drowsy pattern included an increase in background theta.

A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 51-year-old male with epilepsy, last seizure 1 month ago with loss of consciousness and falling from the chair.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax and Neurontin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was performed with poor effort.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This is a technically satisfactory, routine awake and drowsy EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a modest amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Alpha squeak was noted.  Drowsiness was characterized by slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha rhythm, but deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.  A single burst of hypersynchronous theta was noted as the patient drifted off to sleep.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation produced bilateral driving.
Heart rate 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Additional EEG recording will be undertaken to more completely characterize this patient's epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old male with adult onset complex partial epilepsy, refractory, tonic-clonic, and secondarily generalized medicines.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically satisfactory routine EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage, but there is an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Alpha squeak was noted.
Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, spindles, K complexes, and POSTS.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was in stage II sleep and did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Low voltage, otherwise normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in the routine EEG.  Additional EEG recording was undertaken to characterize this patient's epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old woman, seizure free for 1-2 years.  Characteristics of seizures included oral automatisms and tongue biting, positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, multivitamins, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is a routine outpatient EEG with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  Impedances were acceptable aside from the T1 and T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, rhythmic midtemporal theta activity was noted with 5 Hz activity seen infrequently, left more so than the right.  Stage 2 sleep was captured at the close of the recording with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  No temporal theta was noted at that time.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep, but produced vigorous bilateral driving response with supraharmonic driving.  Hyperventilation produced an increase in amplitude of the background.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through brief stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third EEG for this subject which did not identify epileptiform activity.  The rhythmic midtemporal theta noted in drowsiness is a normal variant.
